# Approach 2: Kadane's Algorithm (Running Sum Version)

## Idea

Maintain a running sum of the current subarray.

* Add the current element to `sum`.
* Update the maximum answer.
* If `sum` becomes negative, reset it to `0`.
* A negative running sum can never help future subarrays.

## Code

```java
class Solution {
    public int maxSubArray(int[] nums) {
        long max = Long.MIN_VALUE;
        long sum = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {

            sum += nums[i];

            if (sum > max) {
                max = sum;
            }

            if (sum < 0) {
                sum = 0;
            }
        }

        return (int) max;
    }
}
```

### Dry Run

```java
nums = [2, 3, 5, -2, 7, -4]
```

| Element | Running Sum | Maximum |
| ------- | ----------- | ------- |
| 2       | 2           | 2       |
| 3       | 5           | 5       |
| 5       | 10          | 10      |
| -2      | 8           | 10      |
| 7       | 15          | 15      |
| -4      | 11          | 15      |

Answer = `15`

### Complexity

* Time Complexity: `O(n)`
* Space Complexity: `O(1)`

